@zhreshold Thank you!
It seems that I can use `SortByKey` in src/operator/tensor/sort_op.h, may replace the sort in `proposal.cc` and `multi_proposal.cc` after that.
However, `SortByKey`  in src/operator/tensor/sort_op.h uses `stable_sort`, which is slightly slower than `std::sort`

How do you like this?

        elif role == Qt.BackgroundRole:
            return QColor(255, 255, 239 + 16 * (self.word_index[row][0] % 2))

With this you may no longer need the `LastDocumentRole` and the first `if` in the delegate, the last `if` in `data`, and you can move `doc, index = self.word_index[row]` to within `if role == Qt.DisplayRole:`. If you like it, that is.

Perhaps it also makes selection more visually intuitive - by clicking a row, you select the whole block of same-colored rows.

![screen shot 2017-02-24 at 20 11 17](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2387315/23317161/7fbebed4-facd-11e6-8b61-47d902abad66.png)

looks like these lines below also get called in the case of malformed data - is that correct?

```javascript
            this.synced = true;
            this.models.forEach((model) => {
              model.synced = true; // eslint-disable-line no-param-reassign
            });
```

I was wondering if we could implement `hooks` as an attribute instead of a callable. It would look something like this:

```python
def main_navigation():
    return [{
        'menu_name': _("Start page"),
        'menu_url': reverse('kolibri:index'),
    }]


class KolibriCore(KolibriPluginBase):
    hooks = {
        NAVIGATION_POPULATE: main_navigation
    }
```

I also wondered in what cases you would want to make it callable -- I guess if you wanted to inherit from an existing plugin class and extend a class method? Can you elaborate on your intent? But anyway you could do it like this using the `property` decorator:

```python
class ExamplePlugin(KolibriPluginBase):

    @classmethod
    def enable(cls, config):
        print("Activating example plugin")
        # Make this automatic and use __name__ ?
        config["INSTALLED_APPS"].append("kolibri.plugins.example_plugin")

    @classmethod
    def disable(cls, config):
        print("Deactivating example plugin")
        # Make this automatic and use __name__ ?
        config["INSTALLED_APPS"].remove("kolibri.plugins.example_plugin")

    @staticmethod
    def main_navigation():
        return [{
            'menu_name': _("Google"),
            'menu_url': 'http://google.com',
        }]

    @property
    def hooks(self):
        return {
            NAVIGATION_POPULATE: self.main_navigation
        }


class ExtendedExamplePlugin(ExamplePlugin):
    """
    Demonstrates plugin inheritance.
    """
    @classmethod
    def enable(cls, config):
        pass

    @classmethod
    def disable(cls, config):
        pass

    def main_navigation(self):
        return [
            {
                'menu_name': _('Disney'),
                'menu_url': 'http://disney.com',
            },
            {
                'menu_name': _('Yahoo'),
                'menu_url': 'http://yahoo.com',
            }
        ]
```

However this also demonstrates two potential shortcomings:

1. The plugin callback evaluation order is reversed:
![ss3](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/8888020/12498500/ec5230c8-c057-11e5-8c89-0014a849b29c.png)
Notice that the *second* plugin's callback is called before the *first*. In general can we find a way to guarantee the order of callbacks?
2. Defining several plugin classes in one module requires clunky `enable` & `diable` logic -- in particular, I can't inherit the base class' methods because it results in duplicate entries in INSTALLED_APPS. I'm forced to override the methods even though they don't do anything.

@chaudum looked into it
We changed the error handling to return 404 instead of 400 if a index/shard is not found.
I think we should change https://github.com/crate/crate-python/blob/master/src/crate/client/http.py#L330

Action result must also contain the request-specific fields. So return the merged dictionary:
`
        return {**request.operation, **{
            f.IDENTIFIER.nm: request.identifier,
            f.REQ_ID.nm: request.reqId,
            f.IS_SUCCESS.nm: is_success,
            f.MSG.nm: msg}
        }}
`
So `type` and request-specific fields will be taken from `request.operation`.

@egede Currently we only have 'new' tests for `Ganga` not any other modules. I wasn't planning on necessarily running each plugin's tests in a separate process but it would be possible. The problem that this PR is attempting to fix is that some things in Ganga read the config on initial startup (i.e. config variables in `defaults_SomeClass`-type sections) and never read them again, even if they are edited by the user at runtime. If we want to change these on a test-by-test basis then they need to be able to re-read the config if there's no other mechanism to override them.

The problem in the (soon-to-be incoming) Dirac test isn't that it's being polluted by values set in previous tests but rather that without editing the config file and restarting ganga, there's no way to change what command `gridProxy.create()` calls.

Indeed I want the Dirac tests to be in the GangaDirac folder etc.

This affects a lot of driver code.  For example:

```c++
diff --git a/examples/platforms/cc2538/radio.c b/examples/platforms/cc2538/radio.c
index 56122447..df4a625a 100644
--- a/examples/platforms/cc2538/radio.c
+++ b/examples/platforms/cc2538/radio.c
@@ -96,7 +96,8 @@ void disableReceiver(void)
     {
         otLogInfoPlat(sInstance, "Disabling receiver", NULL);
 
-        while (HWREG(RFCORE_XREG_FSMSTAT1) & RFCORE_XREG_FSMSTAT1_TX_ACTIVE) ;
+        while (HWREG(RFCORE_XREG_FSMSTAT1) & RFCORE_XREG_FSMSTAT1_TX_ACTIVE)
+            ;
```
